{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"316117a1-83d5-4b28-8136-f58c68a5070b","content":"\n\nIn ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request**. But MAUI has no request pipeline — there's effectively **one long-lived scope for the entire app lifetime**. So `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`, and your DbContext is never disposed or refreshed between navigations.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — gives a fresh instance every time it's injected.\n\n2. **Use `IDbContextFactory<T>`** and create/dispose contexts manually:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then in your view model:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = _contextFactory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\nOption 2 is generally preferred — it gives you explicit lifetime control and avoids long-lived contexts holding stale tracked entities.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b75b250c-27a6-47ab-b331-25013d194ad8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common gotcha when moving from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping, specifically with `AddScoped` and `DbContext`. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request scope — **the entire app is one scope**. So `AddScoped` behaves essentially like `AddSingleton`, meaning the same DbContext instance lives for the entire app lifetime. That's why data \"persists\" across page navigations.","outputTokens":384},"id":"a8bf0a8a-1cb6-4ea5-9296-d231ac7e798a","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:39:02.633Z","parentId":"f8accd76-4778-4eea-a234-f996b93eaa80"}
